Like Father did.

62
00:04:35,279 --> 00:04:37,920
Yes, like Father did.

63
00:04:47,959 --> 00:04:50,040
I've got news,
everybody!

64
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:52,120
You all right, sir?

65
00:04:52,759 --> 00:04:54,360
No. Are you?

66
00:04:54,600 --> 00:04:55,720
Coping, sir.

67
00:04:55,800 --> 00:04:57,279
Hear, hear.
Well done.

68
00:04:57,399 --> 00:05:00,360
Well done. They look like they're
waiting for a firing squad.

69
00:05:00,439 --> 00:05:01,920
Can't you make them
more relaxed?

70
00:05:02,160 --> 00:05:03,879
Last meal
and a cigarette, perhaps?

71
00:05:05,160 --> 00:05:08,720
I can't believe it.
You'll never guess.

72
00:05:09,439 --> 00:05:13,240
Houdini escaped the Chinese water
torture, only to die of a burst appendix.

73
00:05:13,319 --> 00:05:14,839
How ghastly!

74
00:05:15,120 --> 00:05:17,120
Oh, and Mother's
got a telegram.

75
00:05:18,120 --> 00:05:20,319
"Mr. and Mrs. Whittaker. "
Your mother.

76
00:05:22,240 --> 00:05:23,600
What's it say, Father?

77
00:05:24,920 --> 00:05:26,759
Perhaps your mother
should read this first.

78
00:05:28,600 --> 00:05:31,759
That stupid, stupid,
stupid boy!

79
00:05:32,040 --> 00:05:34,759
What's happened?
Has there been an accident?

80
00:05:34,840 --> 00:05:37,000
It's John,
he's married that...

81
00:05:37,079 --> 00:05:38,079
Francophile?

82
00:05:39,319 --> 00:05:40,720
Photographer?

83
00:05:40,800 --> 00:05:41,800
Pharmacist?

84
00:05:41,879 --> 00:05:43,519
And why
are you smirking?

85
00:05:43,600 --> 00:05:46,759
Deploying a smile, dear. One member
of this family may actually be happy.

86
00:05:46,840 --> 00:05:49,000
Don't be absurd. We don't
know anything about this woman.

87
00:05:49,159 --> 00:05:50,319
Furber!

88
00:05:50,720 --> 00:05:51,920
Furber!

89
00:05:52,240 --> 00:05:54,199
Oh, not again!

90
00:05:54,279 --> 00:05:55,240
Madam.

91
00:05:55,360 --> 00:05:57,279
Lord have mercy.

92
00:05:57,680 --> 00:06:01,040
Mr. John is coming home
with his... With his wife.

93
00:06:01,120 --> 00:06:03,519
Yes. Their bags have just
arrived. Congratulations, madam.

94
00:06:03,600 --> 00:06:06,360
I'll be the judge of that.
You can clear up this mess

95
00:06:06,439 --> 00:06:07,639
and get Cook
to send up a ham.

96
00:06:07,759 --> 00:06:09,560
This was sent from Dover.
They'll be halfway here.

97
00:06:09,680 --> 00:06:11,639
Yes, chop chop, Furber. Go
and dress the mutton as ham.

98
00:06:11,720 --> 00:06:13,959
Very sharp, Jim.
Don't cut yourself.

99
00:06:14,040 --> 00:06:16,759
John married
the floozy. How exciting!

100
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:34,639
<i>♪ A room with
a view and you</i>

101
00:06:34,759 --> 00:06:36,959
<i>♪ And no one to worry us</i>

102
00:06:40,360 --> 00:06:43,959
<i>♪ This dream we found ♪</i>

103
00:06:46,439 --> 00:06:50,079
There she blows.
Behold the country cottage.

104
00:06:50,159 --> 00:06:52,000
Oh, Lord.
It's enormous.

105
00:06:52,079 --> 00:06:55,319
So I lied about gingerbread
hedges and obese little children.

106
00:06:56,399 --> 00:06:57,759
How hard to swim
is the moat?

107
00:06:57,840 --> 00:07:01,879
Smoke and mirrors, darling.
Smoke and mirrors.

108
00:07:04,279 --> 00:07:08,120
By the by, smoking, don't.
Apparently, it wilts the azaleas.

109
00:07:08,199 --> 00:07:10,120
That makes no sense.
Speak English.

110
00:07:10,240 --> 00:07:11,920
All will be revealed,
darling.

111
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:18,319
Oh, give me back the wheel of my
car. I'm going back to Detroit.

112
00:07:24,040 --> 00:07:28,079
How romantic!
Here they come! Oh! Furber!

113
00:07:29,759 --> 00:07:31,920
Mr. John and his wife
are about to arrive.

114
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:33,279
I can't see them.

115
00:07:33,360 --> 00:07:34,800
Your tunnel vision.

116
00:07:44,240 --> 00:07:46,360
Smile, Marion. I don't
feel like smiling.

117
00:07:46,560 --> 00:07:48,319
You're English, dear.
Fake it.

118
00:07:58,199 --> 00:08:00,600
The prodigal son returns
in a blaze of gravel.

119
00:08:01,399 --> 00:08:03,800
Father! You shaved.

120
00:08:05,800 --> 00:08:07,720
Hilda.
Welcome, madam.

121
00:08:08,560 --> 00:08:10,920
Hilda,
you do look gorgeous.

122
00:08:12,079 --> 00:08:14,000
It's so lovely
to see you.

123
00:08:19,040 --> 00:08:20,879
Oh! Darling. Sorry, sorry.

124
00:08:23,720 --> 00:08:26,759
Mother,
this is my wife, Larita.

125
00:08:28,079 --> 00:08:30,199
Mrs. Whittaker,
the pleasure is all mine.

126
00:08:31,279 --> 00:08:32,639
You're American.

127
00:08:32,720 --> 00:08:33,764
And very welcome.

128
00:08:33,799 --> 00:08:35,679
Jim Whittaker.
Lari, this is my father.

129
00:08:35,759 --> 00:08:38,360
I fought alongside many
of your countrymen, Larita,

130
00:08:38,440 --> 00:08:40,960
and I must say it's an honor
to have a comrade in the family.

131
00:08:41,080 --> 00:08:44,240
Thank you. I do hope
I'm not a disappointment.

132
00:08:44,320 --> 00:08:46,799
Far from it.
And my two little blisters.

133
00:08:46,919 --> 00:08:48,519
Hilda and Marion.

134
00:08:48,919 --> 00:08:51,000
Aren't you the woman
who won the Grand Prix?

135
00:08:51,080 --> 00:08:53,279
Yes. First place,
before disqualification.

136
00:08:53,360 --> 00:08:56,039
Apparently, you need chest
hair to change gears in Monaco.

137
00:08:57,440 --> 00:09:01,360
I saw you in the paper. I cut
your head out. I could just die!

138
00:09:03,159 --> 00:09:06,480
Furber, that suitcase to the
drawing room and do be careful.

139
00:09:07,240 --> 00:09:10,600
Marion. Golly, you're not
a bit like what we imagined.

140
00:09:10,679 --> 00:09:13,600
Someone older, I expect.
Awfully sorry about that.

141
00:09:16,639 --> 00:09:18,559
Before the frostbite
sets in...

142
00:09:18,639 --> 00:09:22,519
Yes. I'm so looking forward to getting
acquainted with the mother of my Panda.

143
00:09:23,080 --> 00:09:25,320
You'll find me quite
uncomplicated, I'm afraid.

144
00:09:26,600 --> 00:09:28,399
Oh! What are you doing?

145
00:09:28,480 --> 00:09:29,919
Carrying you over
the finish line.

146
00:09:33,840 --> 00:09:34,840
Oh!

147
00:09:34,919 --> 00:09:37,759
Venus de Milo,
meet my Venus Detroit.

148
00:09:37,960 --> 00:09:39,399
Hello.

149
00:09:39,480 --> 00:09:41,639
Mother's turned our old
nursery into a boudoir.

150
00:09:41,720 --> 00:09:44,039
I wouldn't exactly
call it a boudoir, Hilda.

151
00:09:44,120 --> 00:09:47,279
Marvelous. All those grubby
memories of Little Johnny.

152
00:09:47,360 --> 00:09:49,399
We didn't even have time
to raid the hothouse.

153
00:09:49,639 --> 00:09:51,639
I only hope we can
make you comfortable.

154
00:09:51,720 --> 00:09:54,799
Please, don't go to any trouble.
We're only staying a few days.

155
00:09:57,879 --> 00:10:00,039
Aren't we, Johnny?
Of course.

156
00:10:00,159 --> 00:10:02,000
And for our
next surprise...

157
00:10:06,519 --> 00:10:08,080
What on earth is that?

158
00:10:10,559 --> 00:10:12,919
His Master's Voice! A wedding
gift from us to you all.

159
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:16,039
How divine! You should
have got married years ago!

160
00:10:16,120 --> 00:10:20,000
<i>♪ Another bride, another June</i>

161
00:10:20,080 --> 00:10:23,879
<i>♪ Another sunny honeymoon</i>

162
00:10:23,960 --> 00:10:26,600
<i>♪ Another season,
another reason</i>

163
00:10:32,039 --> 00:10:33,279
Come on, little blister. Twirl for me.

164
00:10:34,519 --> 00:10:37,080
I see you're connoisseurs
of the great masters

165
00:10:38,240 --> 00:10:40,360
Yes we avoid them
at all costs

166
00:10:40,440 --> 00:10:44,320
Oh! A continental education. Not
all of us have been so fortunate.

167
00:10:44,399 --> 00:10:48,639
Yes. What an emotional depiction of the
French postal service, Mrs. Whittaker.

168
00:10:48,720 --> 00:10:51,679
Come now, Lari. Not "Mrs.
Whittaker. " It's "Mother" now.

169
00:10:51,759 --> 00:10:54,600
Oh, I don't think we're quite
ready for that yet, darling.

170
00:10:54,679 --> 00:10:58,000
Well, since time is
so clearly against us,

171
00:10:58,080 --> 00:11:00,480
why don't you show Larita
up to the nursery?

172
00:11:01,039 --> 00:11:02,240
Dinner's at 8:00.

173
00:11:03,799 --> 00:11:05,679
You didn't tell them?

174
00:11:05,759 --> 00:11:06,960
One bombshell
at a time, darling.

175
00:11:07,039 --> 00:11:09,240
That's not fair!
Your poor mother.

176
00:11:09,759 --> 00:11:11,080
How long are we staying?

177
00:11:11,720 --> 00:11:13,039
A few days?

178
00:11:13,759 --> 00:11:16,000
I shoulder the shortcomings
of this family for generations

179
00:11:16,080 --> 00:11:19,440
and what do I get in return?
A few days. And look at her.

180
00:11:19,519 --> 00:11:21,320
What am I supposed to do
with the bauble of a woman?

181
00:11:21,399 --> 00:11:23,360
Hang her?
I think she's splendid.

182
00:11:23,440 --> 00:11:26,159
Oh, do you, Hilda?
Well, we can all relax.

183
00:11:26,240 --> 00:11:27,480
She's not what I expected.

184
00:11:27,559 --> 00:11:28,840
She's exactly what I expected.

185
00:11:28,919 --> 00:11:30,960
Surely not exactly?
She wasn't drunk.

186
00:11:31,039 --> 00:11:34,080
Very funny, Jim. Reduce
this to the burlesque.

187
00:11:34,159 --> 00:11:36,600
She looks so expensive!

188
00:11:36,679 --> 00:11:38,000
Very.

189
00:11:38,519 --> 00:11:40,279
I like her.
Yes, Jim.

190
00:11:40,360 --> 00:11:42,120
We all know
what you like.

191
00:11:42,200 --> 00:11:43,440
Mother!

192
00:11:50,399 --> 00:11:53,320
Hmm. We have all been
sent to our wombs.

193
00:11:55,200 --> 00:11:56,840
And so toasty.

194
00:11:56,919 --> 00:11:58,559
Economics in action.

195
00:11:58,639 --> 00:12:00,360
She keeps half the house
closed to save on heating.

196
00:12:01,679 --> 00:12:03,759
Well, that explains
the frosty reception.

197
00:12:04,639 --> 00:12:07,840
Well, darling.
Let me warm you up.

198
00:12:30,120 --> 00:12:31,120
Well?

199
00:12:31,200 --> 00:12:33,080
She's lovely, John.
I'm very proud of you.

200
00:12:33,159 --> 00:12:34,440
Thanks, Father.

201
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:36,240
John.

202
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:38,919
How long is a few days?

203
00:12:39,519 --> 00:12:42,279
Mother, Larita and I would
like to find a home in London.

204
00:12:42,360 --> 00:12:44,000
But this is your home.

205
00:12:44,080 --> 00:12:45,720
A home of their own.

206
00:12:46,080 --> 00:12:47,159
But...

207
00:12:48,399 --> 00:12:50,200
But, Panda,
we need you here.

208
00:12:50,879 --> 00:12:53,320
Since you went off on your
quick jaunt around the Riviera,

209
00:12:53,399 --> 00:12:55,240
we've had to let go
of six more people.

210
00:12:55,320 --> 00:12:57,759
Mother, if you'd just listened to
me and taken on some machinery...

211
00:12:57,879 --> 00:13:01,440
Wouldn't that be a good idea? I could
run the entire estate single-handedly.

212
00:13:01,519 --> 00:13:05,080
Congratulations on your
insight and your spontaneity.

213
00:13:05,159 --> 00:13:06,519
Sarah and Phillip
are coming to dinner tonight,

214
00:13:06,600 --> 00:13:10,399
and I have got a table plan that will
take the League of Nations to unravel.

215
00:13:10,879 --> 00:13:12,960
Tonight?
That's absolutely splendid!

216
00:13:13,039 --> 00:13:15,480
Don't be so fickle
in your affections, John.

217
00:13:15,840 --> 00:13:18,440
Sarah might not be as
accommodating as you expect.

218
00:13:18,519 --> 00:13:20,840
Codswallop.
She'll be delighted.

219
00:13:20,919 --> 00:13:22,799
If Mother was so desperate
for her hand in marriage,

220
00:13:22,879 --> 00:13:24,279
she should have
asked for it herself.

221
00:13:24,720 --> 00:13:26,879
Strange as it may seem,
I agree with your sister.

222
00:13:27,240 --> 00:13:28,440
I think you're wrong.

223
00:13:28,960 --> 00:13:30,240
On certain things, yes.

224
00:13:32,159 --> 00:13:33,240
Call her.

225
00:13:33,480 --> 00:13:34,480
Really?
Really.

226
00:13:34,559 --> 00:13:35,639
Really!

227
00:13:36,240 --> 00:13:38,840
If Edgar were here,
he'd do the manly thing.

228
00:13:39,279 --> 00:13:41,279
What? Run away?

229
00:13:45,879 --> 00:13:47,080
Here they come!

230
00:14:01,759 --> 00:14:04,039
And the checkered flag
goes to...

231
00:14:04,440 --> 00:14:05,840
Fast work, John.

232
00:14:06,720 --> 00:14:08,000
I should have
written you, Sarah,

233
00:14:08,080 --> 00:14:10,240
but it all happened so fast,
I didn't know where I was.

234
00:14:10,320 --> 00:14:12,320
In Larita's arms,
it seems.

235
00:14:12,399 --> 00:14:13,519
Please don't be disappointed.

236
00:14:13,600 --> 00:14:15,159
Of course I'm disappointed,

237
00:14:15,559 --> 00:14:18,600
but tell me you're happy, and
I'll tell you you're forgiven.

238
00:14:18,840 --> 00:14:22,600
You're the top. You're
Mahatma Gandhi. You're the top.

239
00:14:22,759 --> 00:14:25,320
Panda, don't break out
the brandy just yet.

240
00:14:25,799 --> 00:14:26,960
To hell we're not.

241
00:14:27,480 --> 00:14:28,960
Have I missed something?

242
00:14:29,039 --> 00:14:31,240
Let
sleeping cows stand.

243
00:14:31,320 --> 00:14:33,320
Oh, you plonker!

244
00:14:33,799 --> 00:14:36,559
Rule one,
push sleeping cow.

245
00:14:36,639 --> 00:14:38,919
Rule two,
get out of the way.

246
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:41,240
Rule three,
remember rule two.

247
00:14:41,320 --> 00:14:44,559
Sarah! It's so
lovely to see you.

248
00:14:44,639 --> 00:14:46,919
I hear your poor father
is not having a good day.

249
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:49,360
I'm afraid not.
He sends his love.

250
00:14:49,440 --> 00:14:52,960
You are a jolly good sport, turning
up like this. That's all I can say.

251
00:14:53,039 --> 00:14:56,639
I wouldn't miss it for the world.
Larita is such a pretty name.

252
00:14:56,720 --> 00:14:58,879
Yes. Excellent
for musical comedy.

253
00:14:59,159 --> 00:15:00,639
Hilda!
Phillip,

254
00:15:00,759 --> 00:15:02,919
I hear the cow is in a
terrible way. I've sent flowers.

255
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:05,360
And did she eat them?
Touche!

256
00:15:05,440 --> 00:15:07,320
Good evening
to you all.

257
00:15:08,480 --> 00:15:10,600
Nobody told me
tonight was fancy dress!

258
00:15:10,720 --> 00:15:12,639
Then why have you come
as the village idiot?

259
00:15:15,320 --> 00:15:17,480
I think I'm snagged.

260
00:15:17,639 --> 00:15:19,159
Let me
help you with that.

261
00:15:23,159 --> 00:15:24,960
Holy mother!

262
00:15:25,679 --> 00:15:26,799
Panda?

263
00:15:27,639 --> 00:15:30,840
You're forgiven,
tenfold.

264
00:15:36,480 --> 00:15:40,320
Sarah Hurst, I'd like
to introduce my wife,

265
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:42,480
Larita Whittaker.

266
00:15:42,840 --> 00:15:45,399
Gosh, I do like
the sound of that.

267
00:15:45,600 --> 00:15:47,960
Sarah, finally.

268
00:15:48,039 --> 00:15:50,080
Johnny talks about you
constantly.

269
00:15:50,159 --> 00:15:52,000
How very annoying for you.

270
00:15:52,080 --> 00:15:53,759
I hope we can be friends.

271
00:15:54,000 --> 00:15:56,799
We already are.
Congratulations.

272
00:15:56,879 --> 00:15:59,200
And I'd like
to be friends, too.

273
00:15:59,879 --> 00:16:01,879
Larita,
my tiresome brother...

274
00:16:01,960 --> 00:16:03,720
The dishonorable
Phillip Hurst.

275
00:16:03,799 --> 00:16:06,240
Charmed, my dear lady.
Indeed.

276
00:16:06,360 --> 00:16:08,799
Phillip,
won't you escort me in?

277
00:16:08,879 --> 00:16:12,159
Of course, my beautiful
little Sausage Fingers.

278
00:16:12,279 --> 00:16:15,000
Well, that's whet my appetite.
Shall we adjourn to the dining room?

279
00:16:15,080 --> 00:16:16,759
And toast my beautiful bride.

280
00:16:16,840 --> 00:16:17,840
Yes, John.

281
00:16:17,919 --> 00:16:19,799
Had we known there was
to be a wedding reception,

282
00:16:19,879 --> 00:16:22,360
we could have all
lashed out on taffeta.

283
00:16:22,720 --> 00:16:25,840
She's a lot like drowning, quite
pleasant once you stop struggling.

284
00:16:26,039 --> 00:16:29,039
So, tell me, John. Was Larita's
family able to attend the wedding?

285
00:16:30,200 --> 00:16:31,960
Phillip!

286
00:16:37,919 --> 00:16:39,240
More cabbage, madam?
No, thank you.

287
00:16:39,320 --> 00:16:42,519
There's lots to do, Larita.
You ride, don't you?

288
00:16:42,720 --> 00:16:44,519
Boats, cars or planes?

289
00:16:44,600 --> 00:16:46,320
No, horses, silly.

290
00:16:46,440 --> 00:16:48,080
Ah, yes, horses.

291
00:16:48,159 --> 00:16:50,639
Faulty steering
and unreliable brakes.

292
00:16:52,399 --> 00:16:54,159
I'm stealing that
for Stirrup Cup!

293
00:16:54,279 --> 00:16:56,399
Stirrup what?
Cup.

294
00:16:56,480 --> 00:16:58,879
Every November, Phillip and
Sarah's family host the hunt.

295
00:16:59,279 --> 00:17:01,679
Wait till you meet their father,
Lord Hurst. He's terrific.

296
00:17:01,759 --> 00:17:02,840
And Lady Hurst?

297
00:17:02,919 --> 00:17:04,880
Was terrific
until she

298
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:06,000
stopped.

299
00:17:07,599 --> 00:17:09,519
Stopped what?
Living.

300
00:17:10,519 --> 00:17:12,960
Oh. I'm very sorry
to hear that.

301
00:17:14,119 --> 00:17:18,960
Between Father's polio and
Phillip's mania for tipping cows...

302
00:17:19,079 --> 00:17:20,920
Can we please just
drop the cows?

303
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:23,559
I think we'll give the fox
a break this year.

304
00:17:23,640 --> 00:17:25,039
No hunt?

305
00:17:25,319 --> 00:17:28,079
Mrs. Winston gave me
her saddle. I've had a wax.

306
00:17:29,599 --> 00:17:32,680
Your father and I conspired to
make John the master of the hunt.

307
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:36,799
People come from far and wide. It's
such a shame to disappoint them.

308
00:17:36,880 --> 00:17:38,319
Very thoughtful, Mother.

309
00:17:38,400 --> 00:17:40,319
You do hunt,
I take it, Larita?

310
00:17:41,200 --> 00:17:44,119
Hypocrites, gossips
or defenseless animals?

311
00:17:44,759 --> 00:17:45,759
Bravo!

312
00:17:45,839 --> 00:17:47,559
You wouldn't get her
to the start, I'm afraid.

313
00:17:47,960 --> 00:17:50,480
We have another conscientious
objector, Father.

314
00:17:51,759 --> 00:17:52,799
Company!

315
00:17:53,640 --> 00:17:55,920
Do you object to the circus
or the slaughter, Major?

316
00:17:56,000 --> 00:17:58,519
I support Sheppard's
position on pacifism.

317
00:17:58,599 --> 00:17:59,759
Good for you.

318
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:02,119
So, when does
the carnage begin?

319
00:18:02,200 --> 00:18:06,400
After the War Widows' Revue,
but before the craft fair,

320
00:18:06,519 --> 00:18:08,000
in between the dog show
and the shoot.

321
00:18:08,079 --> 00:18:09,759
And don't forget
the highlight.

322
00:18:09,839 --> 00:18:12,759
Mother's Christmas dance is
the hot ticket of the season.

323
00:18:12,839 --> 00:18:16,079
She's ordered the most
exquisite Japanese lanterns.

324
00:18:16,160 --> 00:18:17,119
From Japan?

325
00:18:17,240 --> 00:18:18,920
No, Fortnum & Mason's.

326
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:22,839
Yes. Prepare
for a whirlwind, Larita.

327
00:18:23,960 --> 00:18:26,160
I'm breathless already.

328
00:18:30,720 --> 00:18:32,720
I won't make it to Christmas.
You won't need to.

329
00:18:32,839 --> 00:18:35,599
I won't make it to breakfast.
What were we just eating?

330
00:18:35,680 --> 00:18:37,759
The lumpy gray
and beige concoction?

331
00:18:38,200 --> 00:18:41,799
Yes. That's the word I
was looking for, "greige. "

332
00:18:42,480 --> 00:18:46,079
Absolutely no idea, but it
is the specialty of the house.

333
00:18:46,160 --> 00:18:49,599
Incoming! Have you met my
namesake? He's very good in bed.

334
00:18:49,680 --> 00:18:51,079
They'll hear you.

335
00:18:51,519 --> 00:18:53,279
I don't care.
I do.

336
00:18:55,359 --> 00:18:57,799
Look, I know we need the heat,
but please don't smoke in here.

337
00:18:57,880 --> 00:18:59,720
Mother's clairvoyant
about these things.

338
00:18:59,799 --> 00:19:02,240
She loathes me, Johnny.

339
00:19:03,039 --> 00:19:06,839
I'm a gold-digger burrowing in
from the land of opportunists.

340
00:19:08,079 --> 00:19:10,319
Your father's an
interesting study, though.

341
00:19:10,759 --> 00:19:13,119
Quietly sardonic.
I like that in a man.

342
00:19:13,240 --> 00:19:15,920
A fact that won't earn you many
brownie points under this roof.

343
00:19:17,920 --> 00:19:20,480
After the armistice, Father
didn't come straight home.

344
00:19:21,559 --> 00:19:25,319
He caroused around France and
Italy, drinking, having affairs.

345
00:19:25,400 --> 00:19:28,680
A lot of men did similar.
Couldn't settle down.

346
00:19:28,759 --> 00:19:30,319
Why didn't she
go after him?

347
00:19:30,400 --> 00:19:31,680
A question of pride.

348
00:19:32,359 --> 00:19:34,240
He finally just
wandered home.

349
00:19:34,440 --> 00:19:36,599
It's still a bit of a sore point.
We try not to speak about it,

350
00:19:38,079 --> 00:19:39,400
except in public.

351
00:19:39,599 --> 00:19:42,359
You see, she feels she's
missed out on something.

352
00:19:42,440 --> 00:19:44,920
Which means, of course, she's
missed out on everything.

353
00:19:45,000 --> 00:19:48,319
Exactly. The war robbed her
of all her expectations.

354
00:19:48,920 --> 00:19:50,880
She takes one look
at a woman like you...

355
00:19:51,599 --> 00:19:54,039
The harlot stealing
into the nursery...

356
00:19:54,759 --> 00:19:57,000
The delicious concubine

357
00:19:57,279 --> 00:19:58,960
with the delectable ears,

358
00:20:00,119 --> 00:20:01,359
nose,

359
00:20:02,279 --> 00:20:03,519
neck.

360
00:20:05,279 --> 00:20:09,359
I could just eat you.

361
00:20:09,440 --> 00:20:12,000
After that meal,
I'm not surprised.

362
00:20:21,119 --> 00:20:24,640
<i>♪ I'm mad about the boy ♪</i>

363
00:21:06,680 --> 00:21:11,279
Dear Lord, thank you for bringing
John and his floozy home safely.

364
00:21:22,119 --> 00:21:23,119
<i>John.</i>

365
00:21:31,920 --> 00:21:33,759
Why is Larita
always so late?

366
00:21:34,039 --> 00:21:35,559
You can't hurry
perfection.

367
00:21:35,799 --> 00:21:37,480
Edgar was never
late for a meal.

368
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:39,480
Well,
he's missed a few lately.

369
00:21:39,559 --> 00:21:42,960
Good morning. How are we all
on this glorious day?

370
00:21:44,119 --> 00:21:45,559
There she is.

371
00:21:46,759 --> 00:21:47,960
Morning, darling.

372
00:21:50,720 --> 00:21:52,559
What would Madam
like for breakfast?

373
00:21:54,400 --> 00:21:56,839
I think Madam will get more
sustenance from a kipper.

374
00:21:57,240 --> 00:21:58,680
But it won't be
as much fun.

375
00:21:58,759 --> 00:22:00,000
Aren't you riding with us?

376
00:22:00,079 --> 00:22:02,000
Darling, I think
it's about high time

377
00:22:02,079 --> 00:22:05,000
that your mother and I have
an intimate tete-a-tete.

378
00:22:06,960 --> 00:22:08,359
Just us girls.

379
00:22:09,559 --> 00:22:12,279
Lovely.
Mmm. What a frightening thought.

380
00:22:15,119 --> 00:22:17,759
Two hemispheres under one roof.

381
00:22:17,839 --> 00:22:22,079
Papua New Guinea,
India, the Argentine.

382
00:22:25,720 --> 00:22:28,680
I may not have traveled,
but the world has come to me.

383
00:22:29,880 --> 00:22:31,599
Are you coming down
with something?

384
00:22:32,400 --> 00:22:35,559
Pollen, but if I hold
my breath long enough...

385
00:22:35,920 --> 00:22:37,039
How peculiar.

386
00:22:37,359 --> 00:22:39,680
Which is why we should
get to know one another.

387
00:22:39,759 --> 00:22:40,799
Where does
one start?

388
00:22:40,920 --> 00:22:42,359
Shall I
make headway?

389
00:22:42,880 --> 00:22:46,480
I was born in Detroit. My
father worked in the steel plant.

390
00:22:46,960 --> 00:22:49,200
He was one of the first
lured over to Henry Ford.

391
00:22:49,279 --> 00:22:51,359
Ah. Hence the love
of motoring?

392
00:22:51,440 --> 00:22:53,720
Yes, but
I also love animals.

393
00:22:54,119 --> 00:22:56,160
I am a city girl.
I take chickens to the vet.

394
00:22:58,200 --> 00:23:01,880
You can't be squeamish about livestock
now that you are living in the country.

395
00:23:02,559 --> 00:23:04,119
Which was never
my intention.

396
00:23:04,640 --> 00:23:07,519
I was happily carving out a niche
for myself on the race circuit,

397
00:23:07,599 --> 00:23:11,640
when I was unexpectedly flagged
down by someone irresistible.

398
00:23:13,759 --> 00:23:16,960
Remarrying was the farthest
thing from my mind.

399
00:23:19,720 --> 00:23:20,839
I see.

400
00:23:23,960 --> 00:23:25,640
May I ask...

401
00:23:27,039 --> 00:23:30,279
Dead, unfortunately.
No children.

402
00:23:30,440 --> 00:23:31,440
Oh.

403
00:23:32,480 --> 00:23:34,160
How disappointing for you.

404
00:23:34,720 --> 00:23:36,480
Still, he provided well,
though?

405
00:23:36,920 --> 00:23:41,759
Yes, yes, but there were a lot of
hidden costs associated with his passing.

406
00:23:41,839 --> 00:23:46,000
That beautiful motorcar. Surely
you must have independent means?

407
00:23:47,079 --> 00:23:49,720
Mrs. Whittaker, I'm more than
happy to discuss my means,

408
00:23:49,799 --> 00:23:52,000
but I think you'll be
a tad disappointed.

409
00:23:52,279 --> 00:23:54,200
The car is my sole
source of income,

410
00:23:54,680 --> 00:23:57,160
which makes living in London
an imperative.

411
00:23:58,200 --> 00:24:00,240
But what will John
do in the city?

412
00:24:00,920 --> 00:24:03,359
Work. It's not uncommon.

413
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:08,880
John was brought up
in the country, Larita.

414
00:24:09,240 --> 00:24:11,079
Where will he work?

415
00:24:11,440 --> 00:24:14,960
Chalk Farm, perhaps?
Or St. Martin's-in-the-Fields?

416
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:19,920
I know this is not perfect, so that's
why I'm asking for your guidance.

417
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:23,279
So, please, how can I make
this pleasant for everybody?

418
00:24:23,359 --> 00:24:28,400
Well, wartime experience dictates
that you keep your head down

419
00:24:28,480 --> 00:24:30,279
and you fit in
as well as you can.

420
00:24:31,039 --> 00:24:33,000
<i>Oh, there's a war on?
Oh, no.</i>

421
00:24:33,240 --> 00:24:34,599
Not necessarily.

422
00:24:36,200 --> 00:24:37,720
Australian mimosa.

423
00:24:38,200 --> 00:24:39,680
Mmm. Beautiful.

424
00:24:40,960 --> 00:24:42,400
Oh!

425
00:24:47,720 --> 00:24:50,319
And then the British troops
opened fire.

426
00:24:50,519 --> 00:24:52,079
How grisly!

427
00:24:52,400 --> 00:24:53,599
How'd it go, Mother?

428
00:24:53,720 --> 00:24:56,000
Oh, marvelous!

429
00:24:56,079 --> 00:24:57,559
Marvelous.

430
00:25:18,759 --> 00:25:21,400
I fear storm clouds
are gathering, Mrs. Whit.

431
00:25:21,480 --> 00:25:24,559
Stop being maudlin, Father.
It's the future.

432
00:25:24,640 --> 00:25:25,799
Spanner!

433
00:25:25,880 --> 00:25:30,440
Father, allow me to introduce
Panda's new chauffeuse,

434
00:25:30,519 --> 00:25:32,559
lovely la-la-Larita.

435
00:25:32,640 --> 00:25:34,039
Watch it, Phillip.

436
00:25:34,240 --> 00:25:37,279
My son is prone to fabrication,
but I can see on this occasion

437
00:25:37,440 --> 00:25:40,039
he has been perfectly
frank, Mrs. Whittaker.

438
00:25:41,559 --> 00:25:45,160
Yes, that's right.
There are two of us now.

439
00:25:45,640 --> 00:25:47,960
No shortage of wits
around here anymore.

440
00:25:48,599 --> 00:25:51,799
Okay, stand back!
I give you the future!

441
00:25:56,480 --> 00:25:59,240
All right, John.
You can take my baby out for a spin.

442
00:26:02,640 --> 00:26:04,720
Allergies. She inflates
like a puffer fish.

443
00:26:04,799 --> 00:26:07,079
You just want to squeeze her
until she pops.

444
00:26:14,519 --> 00:26:18,440
<i>♪ You might not ever
strike it rich</i>

445
00:26:18,519 --> 00:26:22,079
<i>♪ But, let me tell you, it's
better than digging a ditch</i>

446
00:26:25,279 --> 00:26:28,240
<i>♪ Working at
the car wash, yeah</i>

447
00:26:28,319 --> 00:26:31,880
<i>♪ Come on, now,
sing it with me</i>

448
00:26:31,960 --> 00:26:34,319
<i>X It's better than
digging a ditch X</i>

449
00:26:47,039 --> 00:26:49,279
The missus is a bit
trigger-happy this week.

450
00:26:49,519 --> 00:26:51,200
Bleeding tinnitus
is killing me.

451
00:26:51,519 --> 00:26:56,079
Well, I like the new Mrs. Whit. Reminds
me of the old one before the war.

452
00:26:56,160 --> 00:26:58,359
Only more reasonable. You can
tell she's run her own household.

453
00:26:59,519 --> 00:27:00,599
Be silent.

454
00:27:01,319 --> 00:27:05,200
Good morning, Furber,
Jackson, Millie and...

455
00:27:05,279 --> 00:27:08,000
Cook, I can't call you
a verb. Your name?

456
00:27:08,960 --> 00:27:10,119
Beatrice.

457
00:27:14,039 --> 00:27:17,960
All right, all right,
it's Doris. Sorry, madam.

458
00:27:18,440 --> 00:27:20,559
Always wanted to be
called Beatrice.

459
00:27:20,720 --> 00:27:25,079
Well, Beatrice, would you mind if
I helped myself in the mornings?

460
00:27:25,519 --> 00:27:28,240
I fear I shall be rising
later and later.

461
00:27:28,759 --> 00:27:31,000
Well, if it pleases,
Mrs. Whit...

462
00:27:33,480 --> 00:27:34,720
The point of the bell?

463
00:27:35,559 --> 00:27:38,240
When I ring it, you come to
me. Not the other way round.

464
00:27:39,920 --> 00:27:41,759
Larita. May I have a word? Mmm.

465
00:27:43,240 --> 00:27:44,519
Come along.

466
00:27:47,559 --> 00:27:50,200
Would you please refrain
from chatting to the staff?

467
00:27:50,640 --> 00:27:53,599
It's chore enough trying to
keep this motley crew together.

468
00:27:53,680 --> 00:27:57,559
I had a brilliant French maid in
Paris. Perhaps I should send for her?

469
00:27:57,640 --> 00:28:00,119
Thank you, no.

470
00:28:00,480 --> 00:28:03,359
I'd prefer to keep English the
first language in this household.

471
00:28:03,440 --> 00:28:04,519
Oh.

472
00:28:04,960 --> 00:28:06,640
Ah, there you are.

473
00:28:06,720 --> 00:28:09,119
I say. Anyone for tennis?

474
00:28:09,599 --> 00:28:10,799
Yes. You!

475
00:28:11,039 --> 00:28:13,240
John, Shackleton wouldn't
let a dog out today.

476
00:28:13,319 --> 00:28:15,680
The fog has lifted and
Whittakers don't do winter.

477
00:28:16,119 --> 00:28:18,279
You go ahead, darling.
I'll play with myself.

478
00:28:18,960 --> 00:28:20,519
No, really.
I'm a lot of fun.

479
00:28:21,119 --> 00:28:22,119
Ooh...

480
00:28:22,200 --> 00:28:24,799
John!
It's brass monkeys out here.

481
00:28:24,960 --> 00:28:26,559
Oh!

482
00:28:28,920 --> 00:28:32,359
Day one of the Antarctic Open.
Mister Whittaker to serve.

483
00:28:35,640 --> 00:28:38,200
Hole in one!
Deuce.

484
00:28:38,559 --> 00:28:41,640
I see your pair of deuces,
and I raise you a tenner.

485
00:28:42,720 --> 00:28:44,480
<i>The Titanic could
have hit that.</i>

486
00:28:45,200 --> 00:28:47,279
Sarah, you're an embarrassment
to the Hurst family name.

487
00:28:47,359 --> 00:28:48,640
I'm going to have you killed.

488
00:28:49,880 --> 00:28:52,559
Good God! What's wrong
with you? No! Stop now!

