00:45:42,800 --> 00:45:45,960
You've got two husbands,
and I've had none.

736
00:45:46,320 --> 00:45:47,920
Well, technically,
I have one.

737
00:45:48,000 --> 00:45:49,400
But you've had two.

738
00:45:49,480 --> 00:45:52,039
Well, I've had two shoes, and
that's a great deal more practical.

739
00:45:52,119 --> 00:45:55,320
I dare say, you've worn
down more soles than that.

740
00:45:58,840 --> 00:45:59,840
John.

741
00:46:00,880 --> 00:46:04,320
Marion, Larita's first husband died
of cancer. Stop being so callous.

742
00:46:04,400 --> 00:46:07,079
Come now, John. I'm sure
Marion can appreciate the pain

743
00:46:07,199 --> 00:46:09,800
of watching a loved one
slip through her fingers.

744
00:46:10,119 --> 00:46:12,400
She's scandalous!

745
00:46:13,519 --> 00:46:16,000
You should hear what they're
saying about her in the village.

746
00:46:16,360 --> 00:46:19,039
Well, let's stop those
wagging tongues, shall we?

747
00:46:19,440 --> 00:46:21,920
Is it true you've had
as many lovers as they say?

748
00:46:24,679 --> 00:46:26,880
Of course it's not true,
Mrs. Whittaker.

749
00:46:28,320 --> 00:46:30,360
Hardly any of them
actually loved me.

750
00:46:30,440 --> 00:46:31,440
Hmm.

751
00:46:33,320 --> 00:46:36,639
Well, that was uncalled for. I
realize it was a joke, but still...

752
00:46:36,719 --> 00:46:38,639
You threw me to
the wolves in there.

753
00:46:38,719 --> 00:46:41,480
Come now, Marion hardly
constitutes wolves.

754
00:46:41,559 --> 00:46:45,360
All right, you threw me to the
voles. Either way, you abandoned me.

755
00:46:45,599 --> 00:46:47,800
Your sisters need
to be restrained.

756
00:46:47,880 --> 00:46:49,280
Restrained?

757
00:46:49,440 --> 00:46:52,119
Hilda breaks loose once and
she's almost institutionalized.

758
00:46:52,199 --> 00:46:55,159
And poor old Marion, Edgar
drops by for a cup of sugar

759
00:46:55,239 --> 00:46:57,480
and Mother has his name
engraved on the family crypt.

760
00:46:57,559 --> 00:46:59,639
I mean, I'm sorry,
but it really is very funny.

761
00:46:59,719 --> 00:47:01,079
Hilarious.

762
00:47:01,159 --> 00:47:03,000
Welcome to
the petrified circus.

763
00:47:03,079 --> 00:47:06,280
Meet the resident contortionist
who can't bend any further.

764
00:47:06,440 --> 00:47:10,719
Then stop. Be yourself.
Let them live in your spell.

765
00:47:10,800 --> 00:47:15,360
<i>♪ You do that voodoo
that you do so well ♪</i>

766
00:47:16,159 --> 00:47:17,519
You're right,
of course.

767
00:47:17,599 --> 00:47:20,480
I'm a hypocrite, pretending
to be someone I'm not,

768
00:47:20,559 --> 00:47:22,159
especially since
it isn't working.

769
00:47:24,159 --> 00:47:26,159
What the devil has
that dog dug up?

770
00:47:30,679 --> 00:47:32,599
Pilot, what
have you got there?

771
00:47:34,880 --> 00:47:37,119
How could you not tell us?

772
00:47:37,280 --> 00:47:40,519
Marion, it was an accident. I
am walking on eggshells here,

773
00:47:40,599 --> 00:47:42,679
and I believe I panicked.

774
00:47:42,760 --> 00:47:45,119
And once again,
I'm very, very sorry.

775
00:47:46,440 --> 00:47:48,639
Well, how could you do it?
Well, how could you?

776
00:47:48,760 --> 00:47:51,800
Well, I imagine she bent her legs
and lowered her full body weight

777
00:47:51,920 --> 00:47:54,039
onto the Chihuahua that
was hiding beneath her.

778
00:47:56,000 --> 00:47:57,440
Marion, please.

779
00:47:57,960 --> 00:48:01,000
John, did you have
anything to do with this?

780
00:48:01,079 --> 00:48:04,920
No. No, I was the sole
perpetrator of Poppy's demise,

781
00:48:05,000 --> 00:48:08,159
and ever since I have
been wracked with guilt.

782
00:48:09,320 --> 00:48:12,400
Please, please, please
let me buy you a new dog.

783
00:48:12,480 --> 00:48:13,679
Oh, God!

784
00:48:13,840 --> 00:48:16,920
You might buy your loved
ones in the United States,

785
00:48:17,000 --> 00:48:19,519
but you can't
in the United Kingdom.

786
00:48:19,599 --> 00:48:21,079
How unfortunate.

787
00:48:21,159 --> 00:48:24,920
You could at least
show some remorse.

788
00:48:25,000 --> 00:48:26,840
Oh, I am full
of remorse.

789
00:48:27,280 --> 00:48:30,840
I just refuse to invest in amateur
theatrics to convince you of my sincerity.

790
00:48:30,920 --> 00:48:33,400
That's not how I came off
the assembly line.

791
00:48:33,840 --> 00:48:35,880
I'm sorry,
I can't change.

792
00:48:36,159 --> 00:48:40,400
Not for you.
Not for anybody, anymore.

793
00:48:43,840 --> 00:48:47,239
And I wouldn't want her
any other way. So...

794
00:48:50,679 --> 00:48:51,960
Madam, the dog.

795
00:48:54,000 --> 00:48:55,920
Stay back. Stay back.

796
00:48:56,960 --> 00:49:02,039
I knew it the second I laid
eyes on her. She's a killer.

797
00:49:02,119 --> 00:49:04,159
She sat on poor
Poppy deliberately.

798
00:49:04,239 --> 00:49:06,760
Oh, don't be ridiculous.
Of course she didn't.

799
00:49:06,880 --> 00:49:11,679
My brother has married a dog
murderer. She should be put down.

800
00:49:11,800 --> 00:49:13,400
Put through a divorce court.

801
00:49:13,480 --> 00:49:15,199
The Lord does not
sanction divorce.

802
00:49:15,280 --> 00:49:18,639
The Lord is almighty, Marion. He
can sanction anything he likes.

803
00:49:18,719 --> 00:49:20,639
I say the sooner
they move out, the better.

804
00:49:20,719 --> 00:49:22,119
They move out?

805
00:49:23,079 --> 00:49:26,519
John isn't going anywhere.
Watch and learn.

806
00:49:32,400 --> 00:49:35,239
It's so unfair. Why can't
I have a room like this?

807
00:49:38,599 --> 00:49:42,039
I could die of envy.

808
00:49:42,440 --> 00:49:44,320
Laying to rest
this tragic incident,

809
00:49:44,400 --> 00:49:48,800
we've had this splendid set of rooms
made over for you, haven't we, Jim?

810
00:49:48,920 --> 00:49:51,480
Yes. My wife would
like you to rest in peace.

811
00:49:52,079 --> 00:49:55,760
And I've even had an old friend of
Johnny's brought down from the attic.

812
00:49:56,440 --> 00:49:58,760
<i>Old Faithful Awaits
His Master's Return.</i>

813
00:49:59,079 --> 00:50:01,159
I used to sleep under
that silly painting.

814
00:50:02,320 --> 00:50:05,360
That's very comforting, I'm sure,
but we're expected back in Mayfair.

815
00:50:05,480 --> 00:50:07,639
But these are the largest
rooms in the house.

816
00:50:08,239 --> 00:50:10,039
You'll find nothing
like it in London.

817
00:50:10,280 --> 00:50:12,519
She has a point.
She always does.

818
00:50:12,599 --> 00:50:15,920
Sometimes I don't know
why you ever did wander home.

819
00:50:16,000 --> 00:50:17,320
And miss all the fun?

820
00:50:17,440 --> 00:50:20,880
Cook would like to inform you,
Mrs. Whittaker, the bird is stuffed.

821
00:50:20,960 --> 00:50:22,239
Oh.

822
00:50:23,039 --> 00:50:24,519
What bird? Hmm?

823
00:50:25,199 --> 00:50:27,719
Thursdays is bubble and squeak.
I hadn't made any arrangements.

824
00:50:27,800 --> 00:50:29,199
Oh, but I have!

825
00:50:34,840 --> 00:50:39,840
In appreciation of your understanding,
and now for that delicious double bed.

826
00:50:39,920 --> 00:50:42,360
We'll think of you
every time we use it.

827
00:50:50,199 --> 00:50:52,199
Darling, what exactly
are we celebrating?

828
00:50:52,280 --> 00:50:53,559
Thanksgiving.

829
00:50:53,639 --> 00:50:55,320
Thanks for what, hmm?

830
00:50:55,719 --> 00:50:58,679
The annihilation of an entire
indigenous people.

831
00:50:59,119 --> 00:51:02,199
A loving union
of two great cultures.

832
00:51:02,400 --> 00:51:03,559
Just like us.

833
00:51:03,639 --> 00:51:05,199
How transcontinental.

834
00:51:05,280 --> 00:51:06,840
I can't believe you got
access to the kitchen.

835
00:51:06,920 --> 00:51:10,159
Beatrice did put up quite a fight,
but technically I outrank her.

836
00:51:10,239 --> 00:51:11,679
Who's Beatrice?

837
00:51:11,760 --> 00:51:13,079
Your cook.

838
00:51:13,159 --> 00:51:16,239
Or now my undercook, since
I'm qualified cordon bleu.

839
00:51:17,800 --> 00:51:19,000
That's a degree.

840
00:51:19,840 --> 00:51:21,199
Furber, Furber, Furber.

841
00:51:21,280 --> 00:51:24,159
Can you take the vegetables down to
the kitchen and tell Cook to cook them.

842
00:51:24,679 --> 00:51:28,360
No, Furber, thank you. I think
I'll surprise my alimentary canal.

843
00:51:30,159 --> 00:51:33,760
Well, Mother, if you don't mind, I think
I'm going to eat my meal before it gets cold.

844
00:51:33,840 --> 00:51:35,920
Furber. I've changed my mind.
Bring it back.

845
00:51:36,000 --> 00:51:37,360
Me, too.

846
00:51:39,119 --> 00:51:40,400
Gobble, gobble.

847
00:51:46,320 --> 00:51:47,360
Yes.

848
00:51:52,360 --> 00:51:55,920
Here's a tip, Hilda. A sure way to
a man's heart is through his stomach.

849
00:51:56,000 --> 00:51:57,039
Or his mother.

850
00:51:57,119 --> 00:52:00,519
Larita, look, I've found
another likeness of Edgar.

851
00:52:01,559 --> 00:52:03,719
Marion,
this is Fatty Arbuckle.

852
00:52:04,159 --> 00:52:05,360
Who's in jail,
I know that,

853
00:52:05,440 --> 00:52:08,320
but if you cut out his cheeks
and give him a bald patch,

854
00:52:08,400 --> 00:52:10,199
there's a striking
resemblance.

855
00:52:11,519 --> 00:52:14,440
Edgar's away on a trip.
He's across the pond,

856
00:52:14,599 --> 00:52:18,039
sowing his wild oats
or something agricultural.

857
00:52:19,079 --> 00:52:20,960
She's good,
I'll give her that.

858
00:52:21,039 --> 00:52:23,000
I think you're overreacting.

859
00:52:29,760 --> 00:52:32,079
Lari. Lari!

860
00:52:33,480 --> 00:52:35,719
Not the vase,
not the vase!

861
00:52:36,400 --> 00:52:39,480
<i>Taking the corn cockle
buds and bee-kissed roses</i>

862
00:52:39,559 --> 00:52:41,719
<i>roughly in his
calloused hands,</i>

863
00:52:41,800 --> 00:52:45,840
<i>his hot moist tulip exploded
in her river of delights...</i>

864
00:52:58,559 --> 00:52:59,599
Larita?

865
00:53:01,199 --> 00:53:04,199
Early Christmas present.
For you, darling.

866
00:53:04,400 --> 00:53:05,760
The mind boggles.

867
00:53:13,760 --> 00:53:16,400
Well, it's... It's...
It's magnificent.

868
00:53:16,480 --> 00:53:17,519
It's monstrous!

869
00:53:17,599 --> 00:53:18,599
It's me.

870
00:53:18,679 --> 00:53:22,360
I posed for a young Spaniard.
Don't you absolutely adore it?

871
00:53:22,440 --> 00:53:25,840
Very expressive, darling, but
I can't quite see you in it.

872
00:53:25,920 --> 00:53:27,039
Well, you can see everything else!

873
00:53:27,119 --> 00:53:29,719
You actually took your clothes
off in front of a total stranger?

874
00:53:29,800 --> 00:53:31,840
Don't be a buffoon, Marion. Of
course she took her clothes off.

875
00:53:31,920 --> 00:53:34,159
I think it's unholy.
To be honest, Lari,

876
00:53:34,239 --> 00:53:36,480
I'm not sure I approve
of you being nude.

877
00:53:37,119 --> 00:53:40,000
You know, without...
Without me.

878
00:53:40,079 --> 00:53:41,639
Extraordinary.

879
00:53:42,719 --> 00:53:45,320
What exactly are you
hoping to achieve?

880
00:53:45,400 --> 00:53:48,719
I'm just trying to get into
the swing of things, Mother.

881
00:53:49,159 --> 00:53:50,480
Marvelous!

882
00:53:50,920 --> 00:53:53,639
Well, then, you'll be riding
in the hunt with us, won't you?

883
00:53:54,320 --> 00:53:57,400
Well, I might be persuaded
if the painting stays.

884
00:53:57,480 --> 00:54:01,320
Hunt.
Paint.

885
00:54:01,400 --> 00:54:02,639
Hunt.

886
00:54:03,280 --> 00:54:04,599
Very well.

887
00:54:06,440 --> 00:54:07,559
Hunt.

888
00:54:14,000 --> 00:54:15,880
View, hello.

889
00:54:18,719 --> 00:54:21,000
Hello, everyone.
Good to see you.

890
00:54:21,360 --> 00:54:22,360
Richard.

891
00:54:22,960 --> 00:54:25,920
Morning, Jim. After
generations of false starts,

892
00:54:26,000 --> 00:54:28,760
we finally managed
to combine our cavalry.

893
00:54:28,880 --> 00:54:31,719
Congratulations. A marriage
of minor convenience.

894
00:54:31,800 --> 00:54:33,760
You'll be fine,
I promise.

895
00:54:33,840 --> 00:54:38,480
Now, remember, the second you have the
Holborough boy's eye, flirt outrageously.

896
00:54:38,559 --> 00:54:41,239
But Warwick Holborough has
ears like the Cambridge Cup!

897
00:54:41,320 --> 00:54:43,199
And Phillip's the prize.

898
00:54:43,280 --> 00:54:46,360
Now, if you want a man's
attention, ignore him.

899
00:54:54,039 --> 00:54:57,000
Warwick the Wing Nut
and Sausage Fingers.

900
00:54:57,639 --> 00:55:01,480
What a handsome couple. They'll
have puppies, not children.

901
00:55:03,599 --> 00:55:04,719
Wait.

902
00:55:05,960 --> 00:55:07,599
There's something
I need to say.

903
00:55:08,440 --> 00:55:11,360
I see you, you're wasted here.

904
00:55:12,039 --> 00:55:15,679
When the time comes,
give me a ring.

905
00:55:16,719 --> 00:55:19,000
If I could find your neck,
Phillip, I'd wring it.

906
00:55:19,079 --> 00:55:21,239
Larita's making
sheep's eyes at Phillip.

907
00:55:21,320 --> 00:55:23,079
She's a Venus de flytrap!

908
00:55:23,679 --> 00:55:25,559
She wants him
all to herself.

909
00:55:25,639 --> 00:55:27,599
She's not interested
in Phillip.

910
00:55:27,760 --> 00:55:30,079
Nobody's interested in Phillip.
I am.

911
00:55:30,760 --> 00:55:32,360
Mount up, Larita.

912
00:55:32,559 --> 00:55:34,000
If you don't mind,
Mrs. Whittaker,

913
00:55:34,079 --> 00:55:36,760
I think I might give
the fox a head start.

914
00:55:37,079 --> 00:55:40,159
Lari, get on the pony,
please.

915
00:55:40,239 --> 00:55:42,119
It's just as I thought.

916
00:55:42,280 --> 00:55:46,440
Mrs. Whittaker, I said I'd ride,
and I'm always good for my word.

917
00:55:46,920 --> 00:55:48,159
Tally-ho!

918
00:56:03,960 --> 00:56:08,199
<i>♪ Spy on me, baby,
use satellite</i>

919
00:56:08,280 --> 00:56:12,079
<i>♪ Infrared to see me move
through the night</i>

920
00:56:12,159 --> 00:56:14,159
<i>♪ Aim, going to fire</i>

921
00:56:14,239 --> 00:56:15,800
<i>♪ Shoot me right</i>

922
00:56:15,880 --> 00:56:19,800
<i>♪ I'm going to like
the way you fight</i>

923
00:56:19,880 --> 00:56:23,880
<i>♪ Now you found
the secret code I use</i>

924
00:56:23,960 --> 00:56:27,760
<i>♪ To wash away
my lonely blues</i>

925
00:56:27,840 --> 00:56:30,719
<i>♪ So I can't deny or lie</i>

926
00:56:30,800 --> 00:56:35,440
<i>X Because you're the only one
to make me fly</i>

927
00:56:35,519 --> 00:56:39,840
<i>♪ Sex bomb, sex bomb,
you're a sex bomb</i>

928
00:56:39,920 --> 00:56:43,679
<i>♪ You can give it to me
when I need to come along</i>

929
00:56:43,760 --> 00:56:48,519
<i>♪ Sex bomb, sex bomb,
you're a sex bomb ♪</i>

930
00:56:48,599 --> 00:56:50,199
What is she doing?

931
00:56:50,280 --> 00:56:52,239
A victory lap,
by the look of things.

932
00:56:53,159 --> 00:56:56,320
There's something wild about
that child that's so contagious.

933
00:57:05,320 --> 00:57:08,039
Well,
she promised she'd ride.

934
00:57:19,519 --> 00:57:22,320
<i>♪ No chaperone
can get our number</i>

935
00:57:22,400 --> 00:57:27,440
<i>♪ The world's in slumber,
let's misbehave</i>

936
00:57:27,519 --> 00:57:29,960
<i>♪ There's something wild about you, child</i>

937
00:57:30,039 --> 00:57:32,360
<i>♪ That's so contagious</i>

938
00:57:32,440 --> 00:57:37,360
<i>♪ Let's be outrageous,
let's misbehave</i>

939
00:57:37,480 --> 00:57:42,280
<i>♪ When Adam won Eve's hand
he wouldn't stand for teasing</i>

940
00:57:42,440 --> 00:57:45,519
<i>♪ He didn't care about
those apples out of season</i>

941
00:57:45,599 --> 00:57:47,480
<i>♪ About those apples
out of season</i>

942
00:57:47,559 --> 00:57:52,440
<i>♪ They say that spring means
just one little thing to little lovebirds ♪</i>

943
00:57:52,559 --> 00:57:58,039
<i>♪ We're not above birds,
let's misbehave ♪</i>

944
00:58:16,599 --> 00:58:19,559
Miss Hilda,
telephone from New York.

945
00:58:26,719 --> 00:58:28,159
Uncle George?

946
00:58:28,360 --> 00:58:30,559
Oh, thank God,
a friendly voice.

947
00:58:31,480 --> 00:58:34,559
Yes, and she's
a complete nightmare.

948
00:58:37,079 --> 00:58:38,280
Really?

949
00:58:39,480 --> 00:58:41,559
How salacious.

950
00:58:43,840 --> 00:58:44,960
Come in.

951
00:58:46,760 --> 00:58:48,000
Mother?

952
00:58:49,639 --> 00:58:52,440
I'd like to apologize
for today's schmozzle.

953
00:58:52,960 --> 00:58:54,800
That really won't
be necessary.

954
00:58:55,280 --> 00:58:58,679
In her defense, Larita made no secret
of her disapproval of blood sports.

955
00:58:58,760 --> 00:59:00,360
She did ride as promised.

956
00:59:00,440 --> 00:59:05,960
Well, we should credit her with her
imaginative way of keeping her word.

957
00:59:06,039 --> 00:59:07,760
You must be
very proud of her.

958
00:59:09,119 --> 00:59:10,320
Mother, I think...

959
00:59:11,800 --> 00:59:14,000
I think maybe Larita
and I ought to go.

960
00:59:14,800 --> 00:59:15,880
Oh.

961
00:59:16,639 --> 00:59:18,639
Yes, I see.

962
00:59:19,000 --> 00:59:23,159
Very well. Feel free to drop
in whenever it takes your fancy.

963
00:59:23,559 --> 00:59:25,719
Off you go. Enjoy.
Don't be like that.

964
00:59:25,800 --> 00:59:28,800
I'm sorry, dear, wasn't
Mummy being kind enough?

965
00:59:28,880 --> 00:59:31,400
Here, take these. They might
get you as far as Constantinople,

966
00:59:31,480 --> 00:59:33,199
and this, to Casablanca.

967
00:59:33,280 --> 00:59:34,440
Mother, stop it!

968
00:59:34,519 --> 00:59:36,440
No. You stop it!

969
00:59:37,400 --> 00:59:39,199
Stop being so naive.

970
00:59:46,840 --> 00:59:48,159
The money's gone, John.

971
00:59:49,320 --> 00:59:50,880
Nothing left.

972
00:59:51,480 --> 00:59:54,519
The only thing standing between
this family and bankruptcy

973
00:59:54,599 --> 00:59:56,679
are those surveyors
in the back field.

974
00:59:58,840 --> 01:00:04,239
Lord Hurst is offering to buy 400
acres to keep the bailiffs away.

975
01:00:06,199 --> 01:00:08,079
It's your legacy,
John Whittaker,

976
01:00:09,239 --> 01:00:10,559
and I'm selling it.

977
01:00:15,199 --> 01:00:17,440
I had no idea.
No.

978
01:00:18,840 --> 01:00:20,360
No, you don't.

979
01:00:24,719 --> 01:00:26,360
You were supposed
to take over the estate.

980
01:00:26,440 --> 01:00:28,960
You're supposed to take
your responsibilities,

981
01:00:29,039 --> 01:00:31,800
but you were unexpectedly
flagged down.

982
01:00:34,119 --> 01:00:36,719
I've been struggling for years
with a man who doesn't care,

983
01:00:36,800 --> 01:00:39,079
waiting for you
to step up to the mark.

984
01:00:41,800 --> 01:00:44,440
No. You just go.

985
01:00:45,039 --> 01:00:48,280
Go to Algiers with
your racing car driver.

986
01:00:48,559 --> 01:00:50,559
I'm too tired
to care anymore.

987
01:00:53,119 --> 01:00:56,719
Well, it's not exactly surprising,
John. Look at the grounds.

988
01:00:57,039 --> 01:00:59,000
Your mother is being
very practical.

989
01:00:59,480 --> 01:01:00,920
In what sense?

990
01:01:01,639 --> 01:01:05,159
Well, you're not coming back.
Your father moved out decades ago.

991
01:01:05,239 --> 01:01:08,719
Phillip's not going to marry Hilda.
Nobody's going to marry Marion.

992
01:01:09,320 --> 01:01:13,159
Subdividing the land and selling to a
trusted neighbor is an elegant solution.

993
01:01:13,559 --> 01:01:15,159
Somewhat harsh.

994
01:01:16,599 --> 01:01:19,360
I've had my fair share
of selling off my past,

995
01:01:19,440 --> 01:01:23,280
and it is an auction of innocence
that's neither fun nor pretty,

996
01:01:23,800 --> 01:01:27,320
but it is realistic, something
your mother excels in.

997
01:01:27,400 --> 01:01:29,519
But it's my responsibility.

998
01:01:31,480 --> 01:01:34,239
Gracious, how can I
have been so blind?

999
01:02:13,639 --> 01:02:16,840
Winter hydrangeas!
How do you do it?

1000
01:02:16,960 --> 01:02:20,679
It's a controlled mixture of
passion, persistence and horse manure.

1001
01:02:24,119 --> 01:02:27,559
I was hoping to catch a
glimpse of the new bride.

1002
01:02:27,679 --> 01:02:31,199
Ah. John's wife has
very fickle allergies.

1003
01:02:31,280 --> 01:02:33,719
Allergies to what?
Flowers, Emma.

1004
01:02:33,920 --> 01:02:35,559
Flowers. Can you believe it?

1005
01:02:35,920 --> 01:02:39,000
That is a strange choice of
bedfellow for this neck of the woods.

1006
01:02:39,320 --> 01:02:41,760
We'll just have to make do
with John and Sarah.

1007
01:02:43,000 --> 01:02:45,000
It will be like
old times.

1008
01:02:45,320 --> 01:02:48,360
<i>X When you're smiling</i>

1009
01:02:48,880 --> 01:02:51,199
<i>♪ The whole world smiles... ♪</i>

1010
01:02:52,639 --> 01:02:54,679
Why the big panda eyes?

1011
01:02:56,800 --> 01:02:58,599
Sarah, I've often meant
to ask you something,

1012
01:02:58,679 --> 01:02:59,679
but I hadn't the courage.

1013
01:02:59,760 --> 01:03:01,199
Well, don't then.

1014
01:03:02,039 --> 01:03:04,199
Did you think I behaved
like a cad,

1015
01:03:04,280 --> 01:03:06,400
marrying Larita like that,
without telling you?

1016
01:03:06,480 --> 01:03:08,239
No, of course not.

1017
01:03:08,519 --> 01:03:11,960
You took the opportunity and married
for love, and I respect you for it.

1018
01:03:12,280 --> 01:03:15,360
If we'd have married, it would have
been for friendship and convenience.

1019
01:03:15,880 --> 01:03:17,800
Would it?
Yes.

1020
01:03:17,880 --> 01:03:20,199
We knew one another
far too well.

1021
01:03:20,639 --> 01:03:22,440
I want my marriage to be

1022
01:03:22,519 --> 01:03:26,679
thrilling, romantic,
with passionate love letters.

1023
01:03:26,800 --> 01:03:28,119
I could have written you
love letters.

1024
01:03:28,239 --> 01:03:29,719
Well,
you didn't, did you?

1025
01:03:30,639 --> 01:03:32,159
I did love you
all the same.

1026
01:03:34,239 --> 01:03:35,719
John, stop it.

1027
01:03:44,599 --> 01:03:47,360
He's very different from
the man I met in France.

1028
01:03:48,960 --> 01:03:53,760
The boy.
The same, sweet boy.

1029
01:03:57,519 --> 01:03:59,480
Is it true what she says?

1030
01:03:59,920 --> 01:04:01,559
Are you really
selling off the land?

1031
01:04:03,559 --> 01:04:06,239
To be perfectly honest,
I haven't the faintest idea.

1032
01:04:09,719 --> 01:04:12,280
But it's your home.
It's your community.

1033
01:04:13,760 --> 01:04:15,559
Doesn't that matter?

1034
01:04:15,639 --> 01:04:16,719
No.

1035
01:04:19,239 --> 01:04:21,079
You're a dark horse.

1036
01:04:23,960 --> 01:04:27,119
Have you noticed how few men of
my age there are in this village?

1037
01:04:28,960 --> 01:04:31,800
Fourteen years ago, we all
took the King's shilling.

1038
01:04:32,079 --> 01:04:33,800
We all signed up together.

1039
01:04:35,280 --> 01:04:36,400
My brother,

1040
01:04:37,360 --> 01:04:38,440
friends,

1041
01:04:39,119 --> 01:04:40,320
staff,

1042
01:04:41,559 --> 01:04:45,960
all hunkered down in the
front row of the Great War.

1043
01:04:47,639 --> 01:04:50,880
I thought they kept majors
safely behind desks.

1044
01:04:51,320 --> 01:04:53,199
Promotion for surviving.

1045
01:04:55,519 --> 01:04:58,480
As captain, it was my job to
get them all out of the trenches.

1046
01:04:59,880 --> 01:05:03,800
Within the first four minutes
of our first charge,

1047
01:05:06,159 --> 01:05:07,760
20, 000 men died.

1048
01:05:13,800 --> 01:05:15,559
In Thorverton,
down the road here,

1049
01:05:17,199 --> 01:05:19,199
they were stationed
in Morocco.

1050
01:05:20,679 --> 01:05:22,559
Their captain brought them
all home.

1051
01:05:29,159 --> 01:05:30,960
I didn't bring
a single man back.

1052
01:05:33,000 --> 01:05:34,480
This whole village died.

1053
01:05:36,360 --> 01:05:38,679
I think there's a glimmer
of life in you yet.

1054
01:05:39,599 --> 01:05:43,119
Well, if there is, it has no time for
pet cemeteries and Japanese lanterns.

1055
01:05:44,679 --> 01:05:46,239
Why did you come back?

1056
01:05:46,840 --> 01:05:48,360
I had no choice.

1057
01:06:04,639 --> 01:06:06,239
<i>She came for you.</i>

1058
01:06:08,559 --> 01:06:10,000
Why the lie?

1059
01:06:10,559 --> 01:06:13,000
She thought "wandering
home" sounded better.

1060
01:06:16,239 --> 01:06:19,199
And, to be perfectly frank,
I no longer cared.

1061
01:06:24,320 --> 01:06:25,960
I hate new games.

1062
01:06:26,039 --> 01:06:29,119
There are too many balls.
I can't sink anything.

1063
01:06:29,199 --> 01:06:31,840
Sink some gin,
Sausage Fingers.

1064
01:06:32,159 --> 01:06:33,239
I never, ever win.

1065
01:06:33,320 --> 01:06:35,400
Oh! Well done!

1066
01:06:42,079 --> 01:06:44,199
Stop sucking it.
Come and help.

1067
01:06:44,280 --> 01:06:45,320
Come on, Pops.

1068
01:06:45,400 --> 01:06:47,480
All right, missy, hold your horses.

1069
01:06:48,880 --> 01:06:51,239
All right.
Clear the decks, puppies.

1070
01:06:51,760 --> 01:06:52,880
May I?

1071
01:07:00,679 --> 01:07:02,199
I was hoping
to have a word.

1072
01:07:03,320 --> 01:07:07,280
We're accentuating the positive today. I
really don't have a mind for anything else.

1073
01:07:07,360 --> 01:07:09,440
Of course. Of course.

1074
01:07:11,000 --> 01:07:13,440
I know you're under
considerable stress.

1075
01:07:15,559 --> 01:07:16,800
Regarding what?

1076
01:07:18,960 --> 01:07:21,960
Lord Hurst's kind offer
to buy into your property.

1077
01:07:22,440 --> 01:07:26,880
The realtor I'm dealing with in
London also specializes in subdivision.

1078
01:07:27,199 --> 01:07:30,880
Perhaps he could help
negotiate a premium price.

1079
01:07:31,480 --> 01:07:34,320
Thank you, but really, this
is of no concern of yours.

1080
01:07:34,400 --> 01:07:36,159
Of course
it is a concern.

1081
01:07:36,480 --> 01:07:39,239
I am a member of this family
now, and I'd like to help.

1082
01:07:39,320 --> 01:07:42,400
And this is your
interpretation of help, is it?

1083
01:07:42,639 --> 01:07:45,480
Carving up our heritage and selling
it off to the highest bidder?

1084
01:07:45,960 --> 01:07:48,480
Well, coming from a country no older
than the chair you are sitting in,

1085
01:07:48,559 --> 01:07:50,559
it seems a very
practical solution.

1086
01:07:51,000 --> 01:07:53,559
Just forget the seven
generations of people

1087
01:07:53,639 --> 01:07:57,159
who have devoted their entire
lives to farming this land.

1088
01:07:57,599 --> 01:08:00,639
Get someone else to do it,
with a machine, no less.

1089
01:08:01,880 --> 01:08:03,480
Who do you think you are?

1090
01:08:05,159 --> 01:08:09,039
Swinging your wherewithal
like a cat on heat.

1091
01:08:10,320 --> 01:08:14,159
Now, if you really want to
be of assistance, Larita,

1092
01:08:14,599 --> 01:08:16,680
I think you know
what's required.

1093
01:08:18,680 --> 01:08:19,840
Right.

1094
01:08:21,000 --> 01:08:24,800
I think it's time an expert
showed you how this game is played.

1095
01:08:24,880 --> 01:08:26,199
Watch it.

1096
01:08:26,960 --> 01:08:29,760
Bravo!
Bravo!

1097
01:08:29,840 --> 01:08:33,680
What a sportswoman, I must
say. Can you imagine? Fantastic.

1098
01:08:36,439 --> 01:08:37,880
Lari,
you're confusing me.

1099
01:08:38,000 --> 01:08:39,520
I'm feeling
trapped, John.

1100
01:08:39,600 --> 01:08:41,119
I don't understand.

1101
01:08:41,199 --> 01:08:44,399
It's this house! It has an
air of doom hanging over it,

1102
01:08:44,479 --> 01:08:47,039
and I can barely stand
the weight much longer.

1103
01:08:53,600 --> 01:08:55,680
The answer is to
go abroad again.

1104
01:08:56,399 --> 01:08:57,520
Not yet.

1105
01:08:58,880 --> 01:09:00,960
This is my life for now,
you know that.

1106
01:09:01,119 --> 01:09:02,960
And what part
do I play in it?

1107
01:09:03,039 --> 01:09:04,399
Do you have to be so loud?

1108
01:09:04,479 --> 01:09:07,319
Of course I do.
I'm American.

1109
01:09:13,439 --> 01:09:17,600
What is the use of bickering like
this? It doesn't lead anywhere.

1110
01:09:17,680 --> 01:09:20,399
You never know. It might
lead to a natural end.

1111
01:09:22,439 --> 01:09:23,760
Do you want it to?

1112
01:09:25,760 --> 01:09:27,079
Do you?

1113
01:09:28,000 --> 01:09:29,119
No!

1114
01:09:30,399 --> 01:09:33,159
I just want some
peace and quiet.

1115
01:09:33,479 --> 01:09:36,079
You're far too young
to make a remark like that.

1116
01:09:36,439 --> 01:09:38,239
I can't help my age...

1117
01:09:39,920 --> 01:09:41,159
Grandma.

1118
01:09:44,760 --> 01:09:47,520
Look, I'm sorry that I
leave you alone so much.

1119
01:09:48,800 --> 01:09:50,119
Honestly, I'm sorry.

1120
01:09:52,600 --> 01:09:55,760
Good. Then let's do
something about it.

1121
01:10:01,520 --> 01:10:03,399
Why are we driving so fast?

1122
01:10:04,399 --> 01:10:06,159
The thrill of escape.

1123
01:10:11,000 --> 01:10:14,079
You're looking very game
today, fairest game in the land.

1124
01:10:16,279 --> 01:10:17,680
A penny for your thoughts?

1125
01:10:17,760 --> 01:10:20,039
It's more than pennies,
I'm afraid, Pinkie.

1126
01:10:20,760 --> 01:10:23,159
I don't think I can afford
the party this year.

1127
01:10:23,279 --> 01:10:24,720
But the Japanese lanterns!

1128
01:10:24,800 --> 01:10:25,880
No, canceled.

1129
01:10:25,960 --> 01:10:28,800
Had to choose, Japanese
lanterns or the maid.

1130
01:10:29,000 --> 01:10:31,560
No, you're not getting out
of it that easily, my dear.

1131
01:10:31,640 --> 01:10:34,359
My offer of cellar
and staff still stands.

1132
01:10:34,520 --> 01:10:36,720
It wouldn't be Christmas
without your knees-up.

1133
01:10:49,000 --> 01:10:51,880
This is the first piece of
clarity I've had since arriving.

1134
01:10:57,680 --> 01:11:00,039
Why can't we live in
moments like these forever?

1135
01:11:01,560 --> 01:11:02,840
Why?

1136
01:11:03,479 --> 01:11:06,159
Because you've stopped
loving me, my darling.

1137
01:11:06,960 --> 01:11:08,800
How can you say that?

1138
01:11:09,079 --> 01:11:11,840
Oh, I just open my mouth
and the words come out.

1139
01:11:13,119 --> 01:11:15,359
Then let's make
a fresh start.

1140
01:11:30,920 --> 01:11:33,520
There are so many things
I need to tell you about me.

1141
01:11:34,279 --> 01:11:35,560
Hard things.

1142
01:11:35,640 --> 01:11:37,119
I don't care.

1143
01:11:37,319 --> 01:11:38,600
I do.

1144
01:11:39,680 --> 01:11:44,039
It doesn't matter.
I trust you absolutely.

1145
01:11:44,399 --> 01:11:49,479
<i>♪ I see you again</i>

1146
01:11:49,760 --> 01:11:53,880
<i>♪ Whenever spring
breaks through again</i>

1147
01:11:54,199 --> 01:11:55,399
Come on.

1148
01:11:56,720 --> 01:12:00,640
<i>♪ Time may lie heavy between</i>

1149
01:12:01,800 --> 01:12:07,239
<i>♪ But what has been
is past forgetting</i>

1150
01:12:10,720 --> 01:12:12,119
Stop.

1151
01:12:13,760 --> 01:12:20,239
<i>♪ Throughout my life
will come to me</i>

1152
01:12:20,319 --> 01:12:23,600
<i>♪ Though the world
may go awry ♪</i>

1153
01:12:27,439 --> 01:12:28,520
Shot!

1154
01:12:36,920 --> 01:12:38,600
John!

1155
01:12:41,760 --> 01:12:42,960
Top hole!

1156
01:12:43,039 --> 01:12:44,079
Oh!

1157
01:12:45,359 --> 01:12:46,479
I can't decide
which is worse,

1158
01:12:46,560 --> 01:12:48,880
the idea that you had to sneak
outside to get some privacy

1159
01:12:48,960 --> 01:12:50,920
or that you were
caught by Veronica.

1160
01:12:51,439 --> 01:12:52,640
Who's Veronica?

1161
01:12:53,439 --> 01:12:55,680
I am. It's my name.

1162
01:12:59,000 --> 01:13:00,439
I fail to see
the humor in it, Jim.

1163
01:13:00,560 --> 01:13:02,039
No, darling, you know,
you're quite right.

1164
01:13:02,119 --> 01:13:04,000
I can certainly see
the serious implications.

1165
01:13:04,079 --> 01:13:05,800
It's really not
a laughing matter.

1166
01:13:05,880 --> 01:13:08,199
It's only
a laughing matter.

1167
01:13:08,319 --> 01:13:12,119
Indecent exposure is
illegal, even in America.

1168
01:13:12,359 --> 01:13:13,560
No... Yeah.

1169
01:13:13,640 --> 01:13:16,680
You're right. And we're very,
very sorry. Aren't we, Lari?

1170
01:13:16,760 --> 01:13:18,479
Well, no. I'm not.

1171
01:13:18,800 --> 01:13:20,159
This is my husband.

1172
01:13:20,239 --> 01:13:21,439
And this is my home!

1173
01:13:21,520 --> 01:13:23,880
Well, maybe it's time for the
young ones to fly the nest.

1174
01:13:24,000 --> 01:13:25,239
Certainly not.

1175
01:13:25,920 --> 01:13:27,880
They will stay put
and brazen this out.

1176
01:13:27,960 --> 01:13:31,079
And you can get that ghastly
painting out of my house.

1177
01:13:31,159 --> 01:13:34,079
We do not need any more
reminders of your easy virtue.

1178
01:13:40,880 --> 01:13:41,880
No!

1179
01:13:42,039 --> 01:13:43,800
Help me, Jack.
Right.

1180
01:13:44,439 --> 01:13:46,079
Excited, Furber?
Overwhelmed, sir.

1181
01:13:46,159 --> 01:13:48,119
Jolly good!
Miss Hilda.

1182
01:13:48,439 --> 01:13:51,840
Uncle George.
How explosive!

1183
01:13:52,000 --> 01:13:54,560
Furber, I recognize
that as asparagus.

1184
01:13:54,640 --> 01:13:56,079
Correct, madam.

1185
01:13:56,479 --> 01:13:57,680
Ha!

1186
01:13:57,760 --> 01:14:00,119
I pity poor Panda.
Oh, what is it now?

1187
01:14:00,199 --> 01:14:01,199
Read.

1188
01:14:01,680 --> 01:14:03,479
<i>The Detroit News.</i>

1189
01:14:03,560 --> 01:14:05,520
Uncle George is
a super sleuth!

1190
01:14:05,600 --> 01:14:08,800
Collecting old newspapers is the
last refuge of a truly boring man.

1191
01:14:08,920 --> 01:14:13,039
Boring? Far from it. It was a scandal!

1192
01:14:13,359 --> 01:14:16,159
Wasn't it, Mrs. Morley?

1193
01:14:17,359 --> 01:14:20,640
Mrs. Tom Morley
of Detroit, Michigan.

1194
01:14:20,720 --> 01:14:22,359
Don't be grotesque, Hilda.

1195
01:14:24,000 --> 01:14:27,000
I suppose I'd better finish my
meal before it wilts entirely.

1196
01:14:27,079 --> 01:14:28,319
Any dressing?

1197
01:14:28,479 --> 01:14:30,119
Oh, I am genuinely shocked.

1198
01:14:30,199 --> 01:14:31,920
No, thanks, I always
end up wearing it.

1199
01:14:32,000 --> 01:14:33,319
We've been hoodwinked!

1200
01:14:33,399 --> 01:14:35,159
Mmm. Especially that
runny vinaigrette.

1201
01:14:35,279 --> 01:14:36,359
Fire and brimstone!

1202
01:14:36,439 --> 01:14:37,840
Mayonnaise has more ballast.

1203
01:14:37,920 --> 01:14:40,960
Will you stop this insulting
behavior immediately?

1204
01:14:44,560 --> 01:14:46,000
Hmm.

1205
01:14:47,800 --> 01:14:49,960
I always hated that
photo of myself.

1206
01:14:50,039 --> 01:14:52,000
Of everything
I've ever expected,

1207
01:14:52,079 --> 01:14:54,079
nothing could have
prepared me for this.

1208
01:14:54,159 --> 01:14:55,404
Prepared you for what?

1209
01:14:55,439 --> 01:14:57,840
She was charged with
murder. I was acquitted.

1210
01:14:57,920 --> 01:14:59,359
And that's consolation?

1211
01:14:59,439 --> 01:15:00,720
I told you my husband died.

1212
01:15:00,800 --> 01:15:04,840
Yes, but you didn't tell us how,
did you? Does John know about this?

1213
01:15:05,119 --> 01:15:06,640
Oh, I see.

1214
01:15:06,720 --> 01:15:07,720
It's no concern of ours.

1215
01:15:07,800 --> 01:15:10,239
Father! Really!

1216
01:15:10,600 --> 01:15:13,239
Yes, and after Hilda went through
all that trouble digging it up.

1217
01:15:13,359 --> 01:15:15,880
In fact, I'm going outside for a
cigarette. Would you care to join me?

1218
01:15:15,960 --> 01:15:18,520
Thank you, Jim,
don't mind if I do.

1219
01:15:20,840 --> 01:15:22,279
No concern?

1220
01:15:27,800 --> 01:15:29,359
The pack's closing.

1221
01:15:30,039 --> 01:15:33,600
This woman has taken
advantage of our son.

1222
01:15:33,680 --> 01:15:35,359
He'd never have married her
if he'd known the truth.

1223
01:15:35,439 --> 01:15:36,479
You know that,
do you?

1224
01:15:36,560 --> 01:15:38,479
I suppose you would have
preferred we had an affair?

1225
01:15:38,560 --> 01:15:40,039
Well, I think it would
have been more appropriate!

1226
01:15:40,119 --> 01:15:41,119
Mother!

1227
01:15:41,199 --> 01:15:43,760
Unfortunately,
I agree with you!

1228
01:15:43,840 --> 01:15:45,960
Oh, it's easy
to talk like this now.

1229
01:15:46,039 --> 01:15:48,119
It isn't easy.
It's heartbreaking.

1230
01:15:48,319 --> 01:15:50,159
I love John,
but it's not blind love.

1231
01:15:51,479 --> 01:15:54,479
Marion, does that sound
indicate contempt or asthma?

1232
01:15:54,560 --> 01:15:56,880
You can't palm us off
like that, Mrs. Morley.

1233
01:15:56,960 --> 01:15:58,000
This
is your doing, child.

1234
01:15:58,079 --> 01:15:59,279
You're a bigger fool
than you look.

1235
01:15:59,359 --> 01:16:01,239
Larita is your type,
isn't she, Father?

1236
01:16:01,319 --> 01:16:03,039
That is the nicest thing
any of you have ever said.

1237
01:16:03,159 --> 01:16:04,239
God forgive you.

1238
01:16:04,319 --> 01:16:06,479
Hello,
are we having a picnic?

1239
01:16:08,399 --> 01:16:09,439
John,

1240
01:16:10,199 --> 01:16:14,119
I think your wife better unveil
this one herself. Don't you, Larita?

1241
01:16:17,680 --> 01:16:19,000
Before we met,

1242
01:16:20,479 --> 01:16:23,439
I was involved in a court case
over the death of my husband.

1243
01:16:24,520 --> 01:16:27,479
It was seedy and stressful,

1244
01:16:27,840 --> 01:16:29,920
but since I was
found innocent,

1245
01:16:30,000 --> 01:16:33,319
I didn't think it necessary
to burden you with the details.

1246
01:16:33,600 --> 01:16:34,800
Innocent?

1247
01:16:35,079 --> 01:16:37,880
She was responsible
for a man killing himself!

1248
01:16:37,960 --> 01:16:40,800
The verdict was suicide, but
that's not where it started.

1249
01:16:42,039 --> 01:16:43,960
I thought it was cancer.

1250
01:16:44,039 --> 01:16:45,439
It was.

1251
01:16:45,920 --> 01:16:48,039
But he was so
desperately sick.

1252
01:16:48,520 --> 01:16:51,600
If you would have known him, you would
have understood how forgivable it was.

1253
01:16:51,680 --> 01:16:53,119
It's not as if
she poisoned him herself.

1254
01:16:53,199 --> 01:16:54,359
Well, that's what everyone thinks.

1255
01:16:54,479 --> 01:16:56,760
She's a black widow. I pity you, Marion.

1256
01:16:56,880 --> 01:16:59,199
Really?
Well, I won't let you!

1257
01:16:59,279 --> 01:17:00,279
Right, that's it!

1258
01:17:00,359 --> 01:17:02,279
You have a dance to organize,
I suggest you all get to it.

1259
01:17:02,439 --> 01:17:04,279
Now, go on! Now!

1260
01:17:09,359 --> 01:17:11,319
Hilda! Come on, inside!

1261
01:17:14,319 --> 01:17:15,479
John.

1262
01:17:41,439 --> 01:17:44,000
Are you crying because
you're angry or ashamed?

1263
01:17:46,439 --> 01:17:47,920
Neither.

1264
01:17:49,840 --> 01:17:54,199
Coming here has been the most
demoralizing experience of my life.

1265
01:17:59,800 --> 01:18:01,399
Why didn't you tell me?

1266
01:18:03,319 --> 01:18:05,359
I wanted to, everything
just happened so fast.

1267
01:18:05,439 --> 01:18:06,960
That's not good enough.

1268
01:18:09,000 --> 01:18:11,880
I tried to,
several times,

1269
01:18:13,800 --> 01:18:17,600
but you trusted me
"absolutely. "

1270
01:18:19,840 --> 01:18:23,520
And you saw the field day those
fatuous hypocrites made of it.

1271
01:18:23,600 --> 01:18:25,720
Larita, please remember
they're my family.

1272
01:18:25,800 --> 01:18:28,279
I shouldn't think of them
at all if they weren't.

1273
01:18:28,640 --> 01:18:29,760
Still,

1274
01:18:31,439 --> 01:18:33,239
you should have told me.

1275
01:18:34,800 --> 01:18:36,640
You should have
loved me more.

1276
01:18:38,920 --> 01:18:40,960
I couldn't love you
any more.

1277
01:18:41,479 --> 01:18:43,439
You should have
loved me better.

1278
01:18:46,720 --> 01:18:48,760
I don't understand you,
Larita.

1279
01:18:51,239 --> 01:18:52,920
I don't understand you
at all.

1280
01:19:17,720 --> 01:19:19,199
Are you all left feet?

1281
01:19:19,640 --> 01:19:21,800
Dancing with you is like
trying to move a piano.

1282
01:19:21,880 --> 01:19:22,920
Ow!

1283
01:19:23,920 --> 01:19:26,079
I wonder what the
American will be wearing?

1284
01:19:26,159 --> 01:19:28,439
Or who she'll be poisoning.

1285
01:19:31,439 --> 01:19:34,279
Do you like long
moonlit walks?

1286
01:19:34,880 --> 01:19:37,039
Only when taken by
people who annoy me.

1287
01:19:37,399 --> 01:19:41,600
You've got me all to yourself, Phillip.
Larita's upstairs with a headache.

1288
01:19:41,680 --> 01:19:44,840
And which little fool,
pray tell, gave her that?

1289
01:20:02,479 --> 01:20:04,520
Do you think you ought to go
and see if Larita is coping?

1290
01:20:04,600 --> 01:20:06,359
I already have. She's fine.

1291
01:20:06,439 --> 01:20:08,520
It's been a very trying day
for her, John.

1292
01:20:09,399 --> 01:20:11,319
Go and escort
your wife down.

1293
01:20:11,399 --> 01:20:12,680
No, I wouldn't worry.

1294
01:20:12,880 --> 01:20:15,640
You know my wife, she'll make
an entrance when she's ready.

1295
01:20:21,840 --> 01:20:23,239
Come in.

1296
01:20:26,319 --> 01:20:28,279
Quickly,
you'll blow my cover.

1297
01:20:37,239 --> 01:20:38,760
Why are you sitting
in the dark?

1298
01:20:39,920 --> 01:20:41,000
Watching.

1299
01:20:43,439 --> 01:20:46,920
People are so universally
similar when their guard is down.

1300
01:20:53,279 --> 01:20:56,199
It seems they are universally similar
when their guard is up, as well.

1301
01:21:00,439 --> 01:21:01,600
May I?

1302
01:21:04,119 --> 01:21:06,279
Thank you for being
gallant today.

1303
01:21:06,359 --> 01:21:08,680
You are damn cool
in a crisis.

1304
01:21:09,840 --> 01:21:12,319
The judge at my trial
said something similar.

1305
01:21:15,119 --> 01:21:16,520
Why did you do it?

1306
01:21:19,760 --> 01:21:21,279
Why did you marry John?

1307
01:21:23,840 --> 01:21:27,279
My first husband was older,
and his end was messy.

1308
01:21:29,479 --> 01:21:31,359
Long afterwards this

1309
01:21:33,319 --> 01:21:36,680
boy, this pure boy

1310
01:21:37,720 --> 01:21:40,319
arrived fresh
and unblemished.

1311
01:21:43,199 --> 01:21:46,159
I married him because any
other relationship seemed

1312
01:21:47,359 --> 01:21:49,720
cheap and squalid.

1313
01:21:52,000 --> 01:21:56,079
My first marriage cost me my youth,
and here I am stealing someone else's.

1314
01:21:58,840 --> 01:22:00,119
What will you do?

1315
01:22:02,399 --> 01:22:04,000
The best I can.

1316
01:22:11,319 --> 01:22:12,960
Davis, thank you.

1317
01:22:13,840 --> 01:22:14,960
And thank you, Pinkie.

1318
01:22:15,039 --> 01:22:16,760
No, not at all, my dear.

1319
01:22:17,079 --> 01:22:18,760
Just look at this turnout.

1320
01:22:18,840 --> 01:22:23,840
Hmm. They've only come for a repeat
performance of the Cincinnati succubus.

1321
01:22:24,439 --> 01:22:26,439
May I have
the pleasure?

1322
01:23:01,239 --> 01:23:02,239
Look.

1323
01:23:21,239 --> 01:23:23,239
Tango, please.
Certainly.

1324
01:23:23,439 --> 01:23:25,640
Tango.
Tango.

1325
01:23:32,600 --> 01:23:34,079
Dance with me, John.

1326
01:23:36,840 --> 01:23:38,279
Lari, don't.

1327
01:23:39,279 --> 01:23:42,439
Please, dance with me.

1328
01:24:24,600 --> 01:24:26,319
That was very gallant.

1329
01:25:18,199 --> 01:25:19,960
You've got to
stop them, Mother.

1330
01:25:20,039 --> 01:25:21,279
No, I don't.

1331
01:26:00,279 --> 01:26:03,840
Marvelous.
Marvelous.

1332
01:26:05,399 --> 01:26:10,880
Straight from the bordellos of Buenos
Aires to the Hippodrome of London, maestro.

1333
01:26:11,079 --> 01:26:12,359
Take it away.

1334
01:26:13,600 --> 01:26:16,720
Jim, this is the end.

1335
01:26:28,159 --> 01:26:29,920
Congratulations,madam.

1336
01:26:30,239 --> 01:26:31,680
Have you been drinking,
Furber?

1337
01:26:31,760 --> 01:26:33,640
Yes, madam. Prodigiously.

1338
01:26:33,720 --> 01:26:35,319
You are full of surprises.

1339
01:26:35,399 --> 01:26:38,079
Yes, madam.
I was even arrested once.

1340
01:26:38,600 --> 01:26:40,039
What for?

1341
01:26:40,119 --> 01:26:41,359
Bigamy.

1342
01:26:49,439 --> 01:26:51,960
Ah, there you are, Pinkie. I've found you.

1343
01:27:03,000 --> 01:27:04,760
Larita,
where are you going?

1344
01:27:05,119 --> 01:27:08,039
Away, Sarah,
for John's sake.

1345
01:27:08,119 --> 01:27:09,439
Far, far away.

1346
01:27:11,159 --> 01:27:13,159
Is there anything
I can do?

1347
01:27:13,399 --> 01:27:14,760
You can look after him.

1348
01:27:16,000 --> 01:27:19,800
Women like me are tiresome
in love. We expect too much.

1349
01:27:21,600 --> 01:27:22,840
Marry John.

1350
01:27:24,000 --> 01:27:27,239
It's the way things always should have
been. I'm just so sorry I got in the way.

1351
01:27:28,880 --> 01:27:30,479
You love him that much?

1352
01:27:36,760 --> 01:27:38,680
Go. I'll cover for you.

1353
01:27:39,000 --> 01:27:40,239
Sweet Sarah.

1354
01:27:40,319 --> 01:27:43,640
I'm so glad you've
recovered from your headache.

1355
01:27:44,359 --> 01:27:47,560
Please don't build any convenient
social lies on my behalf.

1356
01:27:47,640 --> 01:27:48,760
Oh, I say,
Mother is only...

1357
01:27:48,840 --> 01:27:50,920
Fighting to keep
the charade alive?

1358
01:27:52,399 --> 01:27:55,319
You've shown tremendous fortitude
holding this family together, Veronica,

1359
01:27:55,399 --> 01:27:56,920
and I can respect that.

1360
01:27:57,399 --> 01:28:02,119
But what I can't respect is the manipulative
road you've chosen to maintain control.

1361
01:28:02,920 --> 01:28:05,800
This war is over.
Move on.

1362
01:28:05,880 --> 01:28:08,239
Move on.
Oh, how convenient.

1363
01:28:08,319 --> 01:28:12,399
Oh, wake up, Marion.
Edgar's not coming back.

1364
01:28:12,760 --> 01:28:15,079
And that ring isn't stuck, you are.

1365
01:28:15,159 --> 01:28:18,880
And, Hilda, you've got such promise,
yet you're squandering it on malice.

1366
01:28:20,079 --> 01:28:23,600
My advice to both
you girls? Run.

1367
01:28:24,960 --> 01:28:26,880
Go see the world
through your own eyes.

1368
01:28:28,319 --> 01:28:31,960
So speaks the siren, leading
the sailors to their death.

1369
01:28:32,039 --> 01:28:34,239
Well, at least I'm not Medusa,
turning them to stone.

1370
01:28:35,399 --> 01:28:36,520
Get out!

1371
01:28:36,600 --> 01:28:37,720
Larita?
Fine.

1372
01:28:38,760 --> 01:28:41,560
Lari? Lari, don't go.

1373
01:28:41,720 --> 01:28:45,039
John, I have to.
I can't live here.

1374
01:28:45,119 --> 01:28:46,600
Nothing can.

1375
01:28:47,680 --> 01:28:50,720
But you're my wife,
and I love you.

1376
01:28:52,119 --> 01:28:53,840
Oh, John, my darling.

1377
01:28:56,319 --> 01:28:58,399
You don't know
what love is.

1378
01:28:58,920 --> 01:29:03,279
You have no idea what it
means to love someone so much

1379
01:29:03,359 --> 01:29:05,760
that you will do
anything for them.

1380
01:29:10,000 --> 01:29:12,840
Even inject
them with poison

1381
01:29:12,920 --> 01:29:15,359
when they're too feeble
to do it for themselves.

1382
01:29:22,159 --> 01:29:25,560
I don't believe that you could
have ever loved me like that.

1383
01:29:34,359 --> 01:29:36,119
Oh, John, let her go.

1384
01:29:38,680 --> 01:29:40,039
Let her go.

1385
01:29:40,119 --> 01:29:44,199
Off into the sunset to inject
another family with her poison.

1386
01:29:44,479 --> 01:29:46,239
Mother.
Go on, off you go.

1387
01:29:46,319 --> 01:29:49,359
Before your past
catches up with you, again!

1388
01:29:49,439 --> 01:29:50,600
Mother!

1389
01:29:54,279 --> 01:29:55,600
You evil...

1390
01:29:55,680 --> 01:29:58,239
Mother! Shut up!

1391
01:30:01,399 --> 01:30:03,399
They are predicting
warmer weather, madam.

1392
01:30:03,479 --> 01:30:06,479
Yes, Furber, I believe
they are. Thank you.

1393
01:30:12,159 --> 01:30:13,479
Very generous.

1394
01:30:14,920 --> 01:30:17,079
There's something special
in there for Jackson.

1395
01:30:17,199 --> 01:30:19,079
Please make sure he gets it. Of course.

1396
01:30:19,159 --> 01:30:20,720
Where will Madam
be staying?

1397
01:30:22,079 --> 01:30:23,399
Who knows?

1398
01:30:24,319 --> 01:30:25,720
Good luck.

1399
01:30:27,279 --> 01:30:28,960
And you, Furber.

1400
01:30:29,920 --> 01:30:32,319
Would you forward the
painting please, Furber?

1401
01:30:32,600 --> 01:30:34,600
To where, sir?

1402
01:30:41,359 --> 01:30:44,319
I shall enjoy passing
on the good news, sir.

1403
01:30:48,359 --> 01:30:49,439
Well, my dear,

1404
